Media notes: Red-headed Woodpecker

Observation Details: The Red-headed Woodpecker arrived in a tree near a feeder and promptly went to all the places in a nearby Oak where Hairy Woodpeckers have been storing seeds. Then the Red-headed starting going to and from the feeder, hiding seeds of its own. About 15 minutes later a Blue Jay stopped by and landed on the feeder (it can't get seeds from this feeder), but within 15 seconds the Red-headed dove at the Blue Jay and drove it off. There was a physical squabble with the Red-headed being the clear winner. The Blue Jay left and in two or three minutes the same (presumably the same) Jay returned with five of his kin. They yelled at the Red-headed but didn't go near it. It appeared that the Red-headed didn't even bother looking in their direction. After a few minutes the Jays gave up and started to feed on the ground. During the 25 minutes the Red-headed was here, there was rain, hail, and thunder. The flurry of activity, including the the arrival of the Woodpecker, may have been weather related.

Continuing pair - possibly attempting to nest.  The birds were in the same area described by othes - a previously logged area.  One bird was at the tree where it had been seen by others, but I didn't see the other bird at first.  While I watched the first bird (probably male) it would fly off and get an acorn, and bring it back to the hole in the tree.  It would present the nut, as if offering it to a mate, but got no response.  It finally cached the nut, then flew off and returned with a bug.  It again presented it's offering, and again no result, so it finally ate the bug, then flew off and returned with another nut.  Later the second bird flew in from the trees near the trail and landed on a skinny dead tree.  The first bird seemed to be trying to coax the second one toward the big tree, but it stayed on a skinny tree which it used as a base for flying off to hawk insects.   Photos

Observation Details: Great first county record and sixth California record found by Liam Murphy at about 10:40am today.  I arrived at 11:30am and stayed onsite until the bird flew off (to the west) at 1:45pm.  Believe that it hasn't been seen since.  Very attractive adult with entirely red head, white underparts and bold black-and-white wings.  The bird stayed put in a clump of about a dozen cypresses seen below the Coastal Trail.   A steady stream of friends and acquaintances from around the Bay showed up while I was there.   State bird for everyone I think.

Continuing pair - possibly attempting to nest.  The birds were in the same area described by othes - a previously logged area.  One bird was at the tree where it had been seen by others, but I didn't see the other bird at first.  While I watched the first bird (probably male) it would fly off and get an acorn, and bring it back to the hole in the tree.  It would present the nut, as if offering it to a mate, but got no response.  It finally cached the nut, then flew off and returned with a bug.  It again presented it's offering, and again no result, so it finally ate the bug, then flew off and returned with another nut.  Later the second bird flew in from the trees near the trail and landed on a skinny dead tree.  The first bird seemed to be trying to coax the second one toward the big tree, but it stayed on a skinny tree which it used as a base for flying off to hawk insects.   Photos

Media notes: This species, when it sits handsomely upright displaying its namesake head, as here, is an irresistable invitation to photograpy. I did not resist the temptation! Even getting this somewhat shadowed photo of that pose by this dramatically patterned red, white, and black bird was highly gratifying.
Observation Details: This Red-headed Woodpecker used several of the trees directly behind the Convention Center. I had no trouble getting photos of it, although, in accord with its reputaton as a high-activity creature, it frequently moved often from branch to branch and tree to tree in search of food, of which it appeared to relish a variety of kinds (see Photo ML49907591). It had been in the area for some days, as reported by others. Because of the late-day character of our visit, the sun was on the bay (west) wide of the woodpecker wherever it landed, and the trees it favored tended to be those directly east of a marshy area that was behind them. It would not, therefore, have been easy in principle to get to the west side of the bird for unshadowed photos. Also, in any effort to get to the west side of this bird (i.e., adjacent to the marsh), I would have had to walk close to it as it foraged in a tree. Thus, any effort to do so potentially could have disturbed its efforts to feed and probably would have flushed it. It would be better, I thought, to have somewhat shadowed images than to interfere with its effots to feed. PLEASE NOTE: This species, unlike many woodpecker species, does not display field-visible differences in the sexes. For this reason, I was unable to declare the sex of this individual despite having close looks and getting close (telephoto) photos.

Known breeding location for this species. We observed them about 2 miles into the trail just as the burn area began. During the course of our extended observation, we saw three adult woodpeckers foraging (mostly in the dead forest on the opposite side of the stream as the trail) and occasionally visiting a nest cavity. We could hear noises from the chicks within the nest, but I’m not including those in the count since I don’t have any idea how many there were. We saw one of the RHWO bring a caterpillar of some sort to the nest. Interestingly, they were extremely efficient when visiting the nest. They usually wouldn’t go fully inside the nest, instead opting to feed the chicks quickly and then quickly fly away. It was really cool to watch them visiting the nest and forage, not something you often get to see around here. The birds themselves were very distinctive and there is not possible confusion species. They had bright red heads with white bellies and black backs. In flight, they had broad white wing patches. The only other Melanerpes woodpecker in this area would be Lewis’s, which we also observed and looks significantly different and darker. As with other Melanerpes woodpeckers, the three individuals we observed showed a high degree of sociability between themselves (and a little bit of hostility towards the Lewis’s Woodpeckers on one occasion when one got a little too close to the nest) and we often would observe two perched together on the same branch. They also were vocalizing frequently, giving both short rattling calls as well as short squawk-like screams. Photos and audio that

A woodpecker about the size of a HAWO was seen on a suet feeder at about 2:30pm.  A quick binocular view from about 30 ft showed the head to be very dark, almost black, ruling out the common similarly sized RBWO and HAWO.  The bird made multiple extended visits during the next 90 minutes coming back to the suet feeder, foraging on the ground under the feeders, eating at a feeder with a hot pepper NoMess cylinder and flying up to branches in adjacent large oak trees.  The initial visual impression of the flying bird was that it had much more solid white on it than the resident woodpeckers.  At one point, it chased a RBWO into a nearby tree and their close proximity showed that the birds were similar in size.  Photos were taken and the bird was slightly smaller than a BLJA and about the same size as a NOCA in the same frame.  The bird had a very dark upper back and a contrasting very light or white lower back.  While the color of the head appeared dark or black while in the shade, the head was clearly brown when seen in the direct sun.  In several photos, the only red that can be seen is a tiny red feather on the throat,

I was on the wrong side yesterday. No wonder I couldn't find them! First heard their juvenile rattles across the way as I was going up the wrong side again. Caught some flashes of wings and that nothing for a while. Finally, they popped out and I got to watch them forage among the trees, rattling throughout. Got some shots for ID.   When facing the yellow posts of the basketball court, they are on the left side. They basically stayed among a specific small area on the hill. At one point, they got spooked by a squirrel who climbed seemingly intentionally up to them on their snag. I have been trying to see this bird species for years and I'm so happy! Thank you to all who submitted their sightings as well as instructions on where to find the bird.   I also tried to record their rattles, but there is too much background noise to upload anything of even low quality.

I found two territories of RHWOs at Fitzhugh-Carter, on opposite sides of the refuge, and this was while car birding.  There are likely others as there are a lot of dead snags out in the open, which this species loves.  In these photos, the bird is caching acorns in crevices of this dead snag just like its closely-related cousin, the Acorn Woodpecker does!  A couple of the photos show over 20 stored acorns jammed into crevices.  Another photo shows the woodpecker with a piece of an acorn in its bill after it wedged it into a crevice, then whacked it to brake it in half.  Several species of woodpecker are mast eaters.  At least one of the photos also shows the bird inside a cavity tossing out sawdust as it excavates or enlarges its roost/nest, or food cache hole.

I was on the wrong side yesterday. No wonder I couldn't find them! First heard their juvenile rattles across the way as I was going up the wrong side again. Caught some flashes of wings and that nothing for a while. Finally, they popped out and I got to watch them forage among the trees, rattling throughout. Got some shots for ID.   When facing the yellow posts of the basketball court, they are on the left side. They basically stayed among a specific small area on the hill. At one point, they got spooked by a squirrel who climbed seemingly intentionally up to them on their snag. I have been trying to see this bird species for years and I'm so happy! Thank you to all who submitted their sightings as well as instructions on where to find the bird.   I also tried to record their rattles, but there is too much background noise to upload anything of even low quality.

Locality: Norridgewock at Persons residence (private), Bigelow Hill Road
Observation Details: Apparent adult bird found by Trevor this morning. At first, following almost an hour of waiting, we heard aggressive rattle-churr calls south of the house. I then saw the Red-headed Woodpecker and a Hairy Woodpecker flying away, maybe the Hairy in chase. At that time I saw the white rump and almost contiguous white of secondaries and that's it. Later we saw the Red-headed Woodpecker well in trees and at feeders. This bird had a habit of taking some food from the feeders and processing it or caching it in small nooks along the trunk of a tree. The area showed signs of repeated visits, and indeed Trevor had seen that behavior earlier in the day. The bird also uttered a low, soft churr before descending to the feeders. Trevor later heard the bird do this repeatedly and captured on audio of that soft call.  A medium-sized woodpecker that looks short in body length but with some bulk. The entire head, chin and throat were deep crimson, with a narrow black bar across the bottom of the red where it met the snow white underparts. Back, wing coverts, and tail jet black. Secondaries gleaming snow white, forming triangular block of white on folded wing. Bill thin and moderately long by proportion; the basal two thirds gray and the tip black. Eye and feet color not noted in the field.  This is a rare bird for Somerset County, with at least one previous record in the town of Fairfield. This spring, 2022, has seen what I think of more than the usual number of the species in Maine for this time of year.

The Red-headed Woodpecker arrived in a tree near a feeder and promptly went to all the places in a nearby Oak where Hairy Woodpeckers have been storing seeds. Then the Red-headed starting going to and from the feeder, hiding seeds of its own. About 15 minutes later a Blue Jay stopped by and landed on the feeder (it can't get seeds from this feeder), but within 15 seconds the Red-headed dove at the Blue Jay and drove it off. There was a physical squabble with the Red-headed being the clear winner. The Blue Jay left and in two or three minutes the same (presumably the same) Jay returned with five of his kin. They yelled at the Red-headed but didn't go near it. It appeared that the Red-headed didn't even bother looking in their direction. After a few minutes the Jays gave up and started to feed on the ground. During the 25 minutes the Red-headed was here, there was rain, hail, and thunder. The flurry of activity, including the the arrival of the Woodpecker, may have been weather related.

Le propriétaire (Rémy Larouche) m’a contacté vers 14 h 45 pour me dire qu’une nouvelle espèce d’oiseau a visité ses mangeoires quelques minutes auparavant. Comme je suis chez un client et que je n’ai pas beaucoup de temps je lui demande de m’aviser si l’oiseau revient. Il me texte vers 16 h 30 que l’oiseau est revenu et je lui propose d’aller le confirmer en soirée.   J’arrive vers 18 h 15 malgré le blocage de la route pour une manifestation et la visite d’un chemin privé qui ne mène nul par gracieuseté de mon GPS. À la suite des présentations d’usage, l’attente de la prochaine visite de l’oiseau débute vers 18 h 30.  Après 45 minutes d’attente et au moment où je préparais le terrain pour revenir le lendemain matin il se pointe...un magnifique pic à tête rouge. Il reste 4-5 minutes.  Je prends déjà des arrangements avec le propriétaire pour permettre à d’autres ornithologues du coin de venir l’observer mais il ne sera malheureusement pas revu. Il n’aura donc été présent que quelques heures.

Found and reported this morning by Gef Chumard. This species has been seen here before and bred or tried to breed here several years back. I ran into Diane Bliss here and we were trying to relocate it, viewing from a berm or old railroad bed trail that runs along the one side of the wetlands. There are a couple of spots where footpaths can be seen going down to the water - there is one with a blue barrel nearby lying in the brush - this is where I found it up in one of the many dead snags right close to shore. It was not initially there when I started scanning. But suddenly I heard a blue jay making a lot of noise just above me and then woodpecker calls that did not sound familiar to me. I looked up through the leaves and saw the jay, so at first I thought it was the jay doing mimic calls. But then I saw the familiar shape of a woodpecker clinging to the top of a tree. So happy to finally get this bird in Orange! All of the recent sightings have been on private or permit-only property.

There was quite a lot of racket--scolding, sparring, chasing each around the trees and off the feeders, as two families of red-headed woodpeckers competed for the suet and seed with not only each other, but also many blue jays, crows, and other woodpeckers.  I saw all four immature RHWs in a single view, but couldn't get a good picture of all four.  Then I saw three adults together....I never saw the fourth adult with the other three.  Each bird is distinct up close.  I can recognize the four immature birds by how light or dark they are, how many streaks on the breast and where the red is beginning to come in. A couple individuals have red beginning to show around the eye or at the edge on the dark.  One of the adults looks very ragged and seems to be molting.  I have been through 15 cakes of suet in 10 days and many bags of peanut nuggets.  Attached are a couple of blurry pictures taken with a point-and-shoot camera through a smudgy bay window....the reflection was terrible today.   One picture was taken on the 5th.

I first observed this bird on the ground, but it didn't stay there long.  It flew up into the trees just across the road.  I was unable to spot it initially, but then I caught some movement as it emerged out of a cavity in a dead aspen tree and flew away.  I waited for it to return, which probably took about 7-8 minutes, and I got a few photos of it after it landed on the tree near the cavity -- with food in its beak.  It went into the hole and emerged again a moment later -- now with an empty beak.  (See photo series.)  The location was near the west end of Kowald Road, in front of a house that's near the road (north side).

Observation Details: First saw this woodpecker about 3 weeks go.  Has now been at our feeder for short durations 3 times in 3 weeks, 2 of the three in early evening.  On each visit, it feeds for a short time, then flies out into the woods at the edge of the property when another bird approaches the feeder.  Can't find a nest but we've never had a Red-headed here repeatedly before or this late in the season.  Over the last 5 years, we've seen a Red-headed twice before but it was a quick look at it out among the trees and then gone for the season.  This year is different.   It's sticking around.

Finally at 5:30, I spotted two juveniles and two adults, flying out from the trees above to the green on the first hole of the golf course. My son and I spotted this bird in trees in the yard after mis-identifying him as a Red-belly or Grosbeak.  Only after we saw him flying around did we know it was a Red-headed Woodpecker, which we had never seen before other than in pictures.  He flew back and forth and eventually fed at both vertical and log suet feeders. Seen throughout the day on and off for two days — August 23 and 24, 2024.  Not too happy to have humans sitting in the yard, but when we went inside he was much more comfortable.  Have additional photos to add after processing.  Also have included several audio files with his agitated vocalizing, including one before we knew what it was.

Observation Details: Birds A and D (Redd and Blaze)  One was furiously pounding a snag while the other was just bip bopping around its territory. Bird A has a fully red head at this point, wing panels are still marked and not fully white. Bird D’s head is about 90% red. Wing panels are whiter, but not completely so. D seems to be tolerating the return of the male RBWP, after being aggressive towards the bird and driving him out for a few weeks.

Thanks to Joan MacDonald Taos Countie's first Red-headed Woodpecker!

A woodpecker about the size of a HAWO was seen on a suet feeder at about 2:30pm.  A quick binocular view from about 30 ft showed the head to be very dark, almost black, ruling out the common similarly sized RBWO and HAWO.  The bird made multiple extended visits during the next 90 minutes coming back to the suet feeder, foraging on the ground under the feeders, eating at a feeder with a hot pepper NoMess cylinder and flying up to branches in adjacent large oak trees.  The initial visual impression of the flying bird was that it had much more solid white on it than the resident woodpeckers.  At one point, it chased a RBWO into a nearby tree and their close proximity showed that the birds were similar in size.  Photos were taken and the bird was slightly smaller than a BLJA and about the same size as a NOCA in the same frame.  The bird had a very dark upper back and a contrasting very light or white lower back.  While the color of the head appeared dark or black while in the shade, the head was clearly brown when seen in the direct sun.  In several photos, the only red that can be seen is a tiny red feather on the throat,

These birds breed here.  This is the second winter in a row they have stayed over, no migration.  There are three of them, two adults and one first-year bird.  It is easy to photograph the two adults because they come closer to the house.  The young bird is cautious and will not come to the peanut nuggets close to the bay window.  Also, the adults spar with the young bird.  All three birds have distinctive markings.  I can tell them apart.  The young bird still does not have an entirely red head and still has some of the brown markings on his back.  The blurry photo is the young bird.  One of the adult birds has a bit more brown in the head (up close) than the other.  The two adults stick together, even sit side-by-side on the bird bath.

Locality: Leesville Road - School Crossing to county line
Observation Details: Spent much time watching these birds. Likely pair, foraging together with repeated “queer” calls, which is the Spring Breeding Call. No “quirrs” or winter territorial calls. One bird, likely female, twice struck a horizontal pose with body elongated while watching the second nearby bird, probably the male, which was drumming and issuing spring breeding calls. Found in area with about 20 snags, many trees without bark, which are preferred for nesting. Although more than 3 weeks early per chart, coded due to breeding behavior, optimal nesting habitat, and unseasonably early spring.     Postscript: pair later confirmed breeding (ON) on May 25, 2020. See checklist at https://ebird.org/atlasva/checklist/S69631877

Media notes: The first RHWO presenting a nut at the opening to the cavity where others had seen one bird inside the cavity.  It got no response and cached the nut.  It returned later with a bug and another nut, and again presented it.
Observation Details: Continuing pair - possibly attempting to nest.  The birds were in the same area described by othes - a previously logged area.  One bird was at the tree where it had been seen by others, but I didn't see the other bird at first.  While I watched the first bird (probably male) it would fly off and get an acorn, and bring it back to the hole in the tree.  It would present the nut, as if offering it to a mate, but got no response.  It finally cached the nut, then flew off and returned with a bug.  It again presented it's offering, and again no result, so it finally ate the bug, then flew off and returned with another nut.  Later the second bird flew in from the trees near the trail and landed on a skinny dead tree.  The first bird seemed to be trying to coax the second one toward the big tree, but it stayed on a skinny tree which it used as a base for flying off to hawk insects.   Photos

Observation Details: Mega found by Liam Murphy.  Many photos.  About 30 people for a big twitch.  See photos.  A spectacular major California rarity found this morning by Liam Murphy. California has only five previous records, the latest being from July 1999. This is the first record for San Francisco County. This species continues to decline throughout its range in the Eastern US where aggressive introduced European Starlings may usurp woodpecker nesting cavities. Males and females are similar. Although appearing to be a full adult, this bird may be second calendar year (SY) or third year (TY) based on small dark spots near the tips of the outer secondaries.

Continuing immature . Seems cautious today. This first-cycle RHWO  now has a fully crimson red, black patch on the back, white belly and rump patch. This birds  performative molt has occurred from October 2018 to April 2019 with a steady and healthy supply of food at a bird feeder.   Photos reveal that the entire head and malar region are crimson red.  Howell discusses these molt cycles of juvenile birds suggesting that the timing is correlated with fledgling dates, migration distance, interannual variation in food supply or a combination of these factors.  Now what is in store for this bird. We do not know if it is male or female and what it will do when summer arrives.. It could be a male and has made this his last stand or will it migrate and try to find a mate in a more hospitable location within its normal range.

*Rare, third time's the charm for me and this bird, continuing in its grove next to "Little Scarboro". Constantly tending to its cache of acorns, flying from tree to tree; it seemed like it was moving cached bits of acorn between cache locations, rather than adding new acorns to the supply. Only once did I see it fly to the ground to grab a new acorn. I didn't see it eating any of the acorn pieces. After a while it flew over to the island in Little Scarboro, and it appeared to be searching in the leaf litter for food, but was uncomfortable on the ground, always immediately flying back to the safety of the trees after 1-2 seconds searching in the leaf litter. Uttering soft rattle calls virtually every time it flew, and also once some "pik" calls. Chased away a RBWO from its territory. A long overdue state bird!

A member of the Melanerpes genus and aptly name erythrocephalus for the adult red-headed plumage. This immature bird has some red plumage emerging on the mostly brown head. The dark, not quite black back is offset by white on the trailing edges of each feather giving the appearance of barring. Some adult black plumage can be seen on the back.  The white secondary patch is interrupted by black primaries also trimmed in white on the trailing edges. A prominent white rump patch offsets the black ratricies.  Most of the previous records for Mount Desert Island (2013 etc.) have been adult but, in this case, an immature bird has taken up temporary residency in this Manset neighborhood because of the numerous numbers of suet and seed feeders which it is actively defending against Hairy Woodpecker, who approached the area calling in advance. There are several dead American Ash trees in the neighborhood which have cavities suitable for nighttime roosting. During the day, it is actively feeding during the 10 to 2 hours. Several distinctive “queerrp” calls were emitted especially when HAWO approached the area sounding a bit like RBWO. Mostly RHWO was silent and hiding on the opposite side of a steady NW cold 30F wind.  Thank you to the private homeowner for permission to photograph and observe this rare MDI visitor.

We've been watching a pair of red-headed woodpeckers daily in the yard for several weeks now, and today they were very active taking bugs and orange pulp back to their nesting tree.  But now, potential disaster. The dead branch that housed their nest completely broke off below the entry hole.  The nest must've been very deep in the tree because both parents dive deep into the wide open cavity delivering bugs and fruit.  We compared before and after pictures and think that the break occurred (likely in a storm yesterday) just below the bird tail in photo 9713. We hope the babies can survive the elements and hawks that nest in the yard next to the damaged tree.  The parents seem very dedicated and attentive.  I hope we will see the entire family at the oranges very soon.

The Red-headed Woodpecker arrived in a tree near a feeder and promptly went to all the places in a nearby Oak where Hairy Woodpeckers have been storing seeds. Then the Red-headed starting going to and from the feeder, hiding seeds of its own. About 15 minutes later a Blue Jay stopped by and landed on the feeder (it can't get seeds from this feeder), but within 15 seconds the Red-headed dove at the Blue Jay and drove it off. There was a physical squabble with the Red-headed being the clear winner. The Blue Jay left and in two or three minutes the same (presumably the same) Jay returned with five of his kin. They yelled at the Red-headed but didn't go near it. It appeared that the Red-headed didn't even bother looking in their direction. After a few minutes the Jays gave up and started to feed on the ground. During the 25 minutes the Red-headed was here, there was rain, hail, and thunder. The flurry of activity, including the the arrival of the Woodpecker, may have been weather related.

Observation Details: Continuing. We were able to confirm all four. Two are in same original area while the other two are in opposite ends of the park, each staying solo. One has a very red head (but brown face) and heavy markings on wings. The one I’ve been checking on has minimal markings on wings and a Red Crescent around throat area, bleeding into breast. Third one is still has quite marked wings with a browner head, sporting red splotches under throat and just under bill. The fourth one seemed browner-it’s the most skittish of the gang-I was unable to get a photo of it, zipped away before I could focus, but while we were photographing its redder companion, it could be heard giving querr call across the road.  We wandered over to try to get on it, but were distracted by the Purple Finches!

I think Liam got the bird here too.

(32.8577462, -100.4688613) first EBird county record by Susan Kosoris. Great find. We were driving to stop for lunch when the cars behind honked at me and Bob in the lead truck - there was a full adult RHWO in a telephone pole but we looked straight up in the sky at a few MIKIs and moved on. When we pulled up down the street in the shade for our lunch break we were shocked to hear that the honks were about a RHWO! We ate a quick lunch and headed back to the area where the bird had been spotted, and after about 10-15 minutes of walking around the neighborhood I heard it calling the high-pitched reedy "prrrt!" call and then Bob spotted it. We were able to get great views and pictures and the group that came the next day was able to find it as well.

Excellent find by Julie Neff-Encinas, congrats! Bird was collecting acorns from oaks in adjacent community park and stashing them in the palm trees where originally located. Plenty to pick, the oaks were loaded. Was regularly giving oriole/blackbird like chatter and cheg call when in flight or irritated. Seemed to hold its own avoiding Gilas. This  youngster is retaining alot of juvenile plumage currently. Interestingly this species varies significantly on rate and extent of molt in formative plumage period. Red was sparsely mottled in face with a large blotch confined to the nape. Most of back was barred with brown edging. Flanks had light streaking and secondaries mostly retained subterminal bar with a cool second bar. This bird hasnt grown up much yet, I feel you RHWO, me neither.

Locality: Leonora Curtin Wetland Preserve (access through Las Golondrinas - fee involved)
Observation Details: Woah what a surprise! First spotted by Sylvan as we were in a huge flurry of activity.  At first glance of this woodpecker, the white secondaries immediately jumped out on an other wise brownish woodpecker of medium size (smaller than Flickers).  Bird did not stay perched long initially and flew from mature Russian Olive group on right (north) side of prairie to the large cottonwood directly across prairie to the south.  Here the white panel of secondary feathers really stood out, as did the white rump.  Was able to get diagnostic photos on that initial flight.  We pursued across the prairie to the big cottonwood for better looks/photos.  The bird flew quickly around 2-3 perches before setting somewhere up high and hidden.  After about 15 mins, we gave up and continued on with survey.  After survey we were able to see the RHWO again, and watch as it come over to feed on fruits from the Russian Olive, and flying some back across to the more dense shelter of the Cottonwood.  This individual lacked the red head of an adult, but instead of overall a dark brown color on head, and back more blackish with some mottling and paler feather edges. Bright white secondaries with an incomplete black barring across and more complete black subterminal tip to those secondaries.  Primaries and retrices more blackish in color, slightly darker than the very dark brown head/mantle.  Vocalizations were limited almost exclusively to a low-pitched rattle or clucking.  1st species record for LCWP.  Appears to be a 5th bird for county (eBird era).  Wondering if this could be same individual as recently found along river at Buckman Road (or from Los Alamos population).

Found and reported this morning by Gef Chumard. This species has been seen here before and bred or tried to breed here several years back. I ran into Diane Bliss here and we were trying to relocate it, viewing from a berm or old railroad bed trail that runs along the one side of the wetlands. There are a couple of spots where footpaths can be seen going down to the water - there is one with a blue barrel nearby lying in the brush - this is where I found it up in one of the many dead snags right close to shore. It was not initially there when I started scanning. But suddenly I heard a blue jay making a lot of noise just above me and then woodpecker calls that did not sound familiar to me. I looked up through the leaves and saw the jay, so at first I thought it was the jay doing mimic calls. But then I saw the familiar shape of a woodpecker clinging to the top of a tree. So happy to finally get this bird in Orange! All of the recent sightings have been on private or permit-only property.

I found two territories of RHWOs at Fitzhugh-Carter, on opposite sides of the refuge, and this was while car birding.  There are likely others as there are a lot of dead snags out in the open, which this species loves.  In these photos, the bird is caching acorns in crevices of this dead snag just like its closely-related cousin, the Acorn Woodpecker does!  A couple of the photos show over 20 stored acorns jammed into crevices.  Another photo shows the woodpecker with a piece of an acorn in its bill after it wedged it into a crevice, then whacked it to brake it in half.  Several species of woodpecker are mast eaters.  At least one of the photos also shows the bird inside a cavity tossing out sawdust as it excavates or enlarges its roost/nest, or food cache hole.

The adult not in the cavity stayed near the fledglings, and occasionally fed them. The fledglings are hawking insects on their own, but still begging for food.

This dead snag sits back in the woods on the left side of Kline Road as you are heading up it from Arneman, about 3/4 mile from Arneman, at the top, just before it starts to curve left.  The bird seemed to be hammering an acorn it had wedged in a crevice.  I watched and photographed it for over 10 minutes.  It was vocalizing.  It has been my experience, in many locations in North American, that RHWOs love to nest in dead snags.  Was this a nest tree?  Will this bird come back to this snag to nest next year?  I will try to keep an eye on this snag next year.

Continuing bird.  Still located in the dead/dying tree 10 yards east of the fork to the boat ramp.  There are 4-5 cavities towards the top third of the tree.  This bird first came out of one of the cavities (for less than a minute) when several European Starlings were near the cavities and then left the tree.  A single European Starling returned to the tree around 15 minutes later and then left shortly after the Red-headed Woodpecker came out of one of the north-facing cavities.  This bird remained outside of the cavity for around 6 minutes, working its way up towards the upper portion of the tree that lacked bark, until a squirrel occupied one of the east-facing cavities.  It then flew to the large tree approximately 50 yards south (towards the river).

On the afternoon of 3-29-2016, we observed and photographed two pairs of adult red-headed woodpeckers near the area where Park Road 1C crosses Alum Creek. One pair of woodpeckers were present in the dead pines to the north of Park Road 1C west of Alum Creek and one pair were present in the dead pines to the south of Park Road 1C east of Alum Creek. In each instance, both birds were observed simultaneously, so I am certain that there was no "double-counting". The sites were sufficiently far apart and the timing of the observations were such that I am certain that there were two pairs of red-headed woodpeckers present, not one pair.

During our drive on Wildlife (WL) Drive, we spotted 4 different groupings of red-headed woodpeckers. The largest group was at the intersection of WL drive and the road to the observation dock. Here we spotted 2 adults and 2 juveniles with an additional adult on a flyby towards the main entrance. On the drive to the observation dock, we spotted at least 3 more flying from tree to tree on our left. About 200 feet further up WL drive we saw 2 additional flying back and forth across the road with no juveniles in sight so it was determined they were different from the family spotted earlier. The last two we spotted were in the woods trail near the exploded boiler. I will admit, the only possible repeat could have been the adult flyby heading towards the main entrance but because I never saw it come back, I counted it separate.

Media notes: Preparing to bring food to one juvenile still in nest hole
Observation Details: The young Red-headed Woodpeckers fledged today. We only saw two  juveniles with two adults but there could have been more juveniles. When we arrived, one adult was taking food to a recently fledged juvenile at the west side of the playing fields about 100 m from the nest tree. The second adult brought food three times over the course of 1 hour and 10 minutes to a juvenile still in the nest cavity. Immediately after being fed the third time and after the adult had left, the juvenile stuck its head way out of the cavity, looked about and suddenly flew out of the cavity to a nearby tree, where it concealed itself. The adult didn’t know the juvenile left because it brought food to the nest cavity and checked inside, but right away found the vocalizing young in the tree nearby. The adult returned several times to feed the young in the tree but never went back to the nest cavity.

Thanks to Suan for reporting it on Cayugabirds! Spent about 30 minutes watching and filming it (not included in the birding duration since I stopped paying attention to other birds).  Cached more than 20 nut pieces in the bark of one tree over the duration. There was one branch on an adjacent tree that it kept using as the anvil to crack the nuts. Sometimes, it inspected the cache and readjusted the positions of some nut pieces that were perhaps too exposed to its liking.
